  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own community, especially with the kids I work with in Chicago. As a fitness trainer, I've noticed how deeply ingrained gender and racial stereotypes can affect people's confidence in their abilities, even when they're clearly capable. For example, I've had students who've told me they avoid science classes because they fear being labeled 'not smart enough' based on their gender or ethnicity. This is stereotype threat in action: the anxiety of being judged by a negative stereotype about one's group, which can impair performance. It's real and it's harmful, but addressing it isn't about fixing people—it's about changing the environment so that everyone feels safe to try. I've seen this firsthand with my own children, who've always been curious about how things work but sometimes hesitate to ask questions because they think they don't 'get it.' The key is creating spaces where mistakes are seen as learning opportunities, not failures. As a curious person myself, I believe the best way to address this is through inclusive teaching practices, like storytelling that connects STEM to real-life problems people care about—like how fitness and nutrition science can help communities thrive. It's not about erasing stereotypes but helping people see their potential without the fear of judgment. In a world where so many people feel invisible, it's our job to make sure everyone has the chance to shine.",
